+# Predefined questions — use long-context prompts so prefill dominates and AMX advantage is visible
+CONTEXT_DOC = """
+Intel Advanced Matrix Extensions (AMX) is an x86 ISA extension introduced in Intel Xeon Scalable
+processors (Sapphire Rapids and later). AMX adds eight 2D tile registers (each 16 rows × 64 bytes)
+and a set of TMUL instructions that perform a full 16×16 BF16 matrix multiply-accumulate in a
+single instruction, delivering up to 2048 BF16 MACs per cycle per core. This is a significant
+improvement over AVX-512 BF16 VNNI, which processes 4×16 BF16 dot products per instruction.
+
+In transformer-based LLM inference there are two distinct phases. The prefill phase processes
+the entire input prompt simultaneously: it computes query, key, and value projections (three large
+GEMMs over hidden_size × sequence_length), self-attention scores, and all feed-forward network
+layers. Because the full sequence is processed in parallel, prefill consists of large matrix
+multiplications — exactly the compute-bound workload AMX tile instructions are designed for.
+
+The decode phase generates one token at a time via autoregressive sampling. Each step performs
+a matrix-vector multiply (sequence length 1 against the full weight matrices), which is
+memory-bandwidth bound: the bottleneck is loading weight matrices from DRAM, not arithmetic
+throughput. AMX provides no benefit here; both AMX and non-AMX cores are equally limited by
+DRAM bandwidth.
+
+As a result, AMX delivers its performance advantage primarily through TTFT (time to first token),
+which measures prefill latency. For workloads with long input contexts and short outputs — such as
+retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), document summarisation, code review, and classification —
+prefill constitutes a large fraction of total request time, making TTFT a user-visible latency
+metric. Benchmarks on Granite-3.3-8B show approximately 6× faster prefill throughput with AMX
+compared to AVX-512 BF16 only, translating to a 3× end-to-end speedup for a 2600-token prompt
+with 50-token output.
+"""
